author: JEFF GREEN
title: Paramus police investigating whether Fetty Wap was involved in ShopRite cashier assault - News
text:
PARAMUS – Police are trying to find out whether a man who allegedly assaulted a ShopRite employee last week is the Paterson rapper and rising star known as Fetty Wap.
The employee told police he believed Fetty Wap, whose hit song “Trap Queen” rose to the top of the charts this spring, was part of a group that attacked him while he was working in the checkout line Friday evening.
The incident started with a woman slapping the male employee, according to a police report. Three other people with the woman thought that the employee had insulted her, and they joined in attacking him, the report said.
The 19-year-old employee said one of the people in the group of two men and two women was possibly the 25-year-old rapper, whose real name is Willie Maxwell II.
Police observed minor swelling on the employee’s face. The employee declined to press charges but was told he could do so at a later date. He could not be reached for comment.
Police Chief Kenneth Ehrenberg said detectives were working to establish the identities of the group, to learn their side of the story and in the event that the employee changed his mind about filing a complaint. It was not clear from Shop Rite surveillance footage or a cell phone video recorded by a witness, which was provided to the celebrity gossip website TMZ, if Fetty Wap was part of the group.
“Maybe it looks like him,” the chief said. “We can’t go by, uh, it looks like him. We need more evidence than that.”
A publicist for Fetty Wap could not immediately be reached for comment Tuesday.
Both ShopRite and the police declined to release the surveillance video.
